# {{ hostname }} Jekyll Site

This scaffold is a narrow Jekyll build-and-serve baseline for `{{ hostname }}`.

## Files

- `docker-compose.yml`: Traefik-connected nginx service built from the local Dockerfile
- `Dockerfile`: multi-stage image that builds the Jekyll site and serves the generated output with nginx
- `.dockerignore`: keeps build cache and generated site output out of the image context
- `site/Gemfile`: starter Jekyll gem definition
- `site/_config.yml`: starter Jekyll site config
- `site/index.md`: starter page content
- `README.md`: adoption notes for the scaffold

## Local adjustments

1. For a new site, edit the files under `site/` and build with `docker compose up --build`.
2. To adopt an existing Jekyll repo, copy the repo contents into `site/` and keep the generated `docker-compose.yml` and `Dockerfile` in the stack root.
3. Make sure the adopted `site/` tree includes the files Jekyll needs at its source root, such as `_config.yml`, `Gemfile`, pages, posts, collections, layouts, includes, and assets.
4. Run `docker compose up --build`.
5. Verify the container becomes healthy and that `https://{{ hostname }}/` serves the generated site.
6. If your adopted site needs native gem dependencies beyond the starter baseline, extend the generated `Dockerfile` accordingly.

## Runtime behavior

- the image builds the Jekyll site from `./site`
- nginx serves the generated static output on port `80`
- Traefik forwards `{{ hostname }}` to nginx on port `80`
- the generated compose service includes a container healthcheck against `http://127.0.0.1/`
